studies.title: Phospholipid acyl chain diversity controls the tissue-specific assembly of mitochondrial cardiolipins
studies.description:
Cardiolipin (CL) is a phospholipid specific for mitochondrial membranes and crucial for many core tasks of this organelle. Its side chain configurations are tissue-specific, functionally important and generated via post-biosynthetic remodeling. However, this process lacks the necessary specificity to explain CL diversity, which is especially evident for highly specific CL compositions in mammalian tissues. To investigate the so far elusive regulatory origin of CL homeostasis in mice we combine lipidomics, integrative transcriptomics and data-driven machine learning. We demonstrate that not transcriptional regulation, but cellular phospholipid compositions are closely linked to the tissue-specificity of CL patterns allowing artificial neural networks to precisely predict cross-tissue CL compositions in a consistent mechanistic specificity rationale. This is especially relevant for the interpretation of disease-related perturbations of CL homeostasis, by allowing to differentiate between specific aberrations in CL metabolism and changes caused by global alterations in cellular (phospho-)lipid metabolism.

protocols.name: Sample collection
protocols.description:
Sample Material

Mus musculus samples were obtained from eight week old male and female C57BL/6J mice in biological triplicates, housed in microisolator cages under temperature controlled conditions and a 12 h light/dark cycle fed ad libitum (11% energy by fat, Ssniff Spezialdiäten GmbH, EF D12450B mod.) Extracted tissues were briefly washed in PBS and snap frozen in liquid nitrogen. The 15 tissues were chosen to cover all major organs that were sufficiently available and were reproducibly extractable without contaminations.

 

Cell culture

Mammalian cells were cultured under standard conditions as described in [1]. Lipid supplementation experiments were conducted in the presence of 25-250 µM fatty acid - BSA conjugates (see extended methods in asscoiated publication).


The mouse tissues, snap frozen and stored at -80 °C, were homogenized as follows:

a. The sample in a 2 ml screw cap micro tube (Sarstedt, Nümbrecht, Germany) was cooled in liquid nitrogen (N2(l)). One 5 mm hardened steel metal ball (Retsch, Haan, Germany, cat.nr 05.368.0029) was added, and cooled in N2(l) again.

b. The samples were mixed in precooled (-20 °C) MM 400 adapters (Retsch, Haan, Germany, cat.nr 22.008.0008) at 25 Hz for 1 min, MM400 (Retsch, Haan, Germany) then cooled in N2(l).

c. Step b. was repeated 4 times, increasing the frequency (29, 29, 30, 30 Hz).

d. The metal ball was removed, and samples were classified visually as inhomogenous/homogenous.

e. Homogenous samples were subjoined with 1 spoon full of glass beads (~ 100 mg, G8772 425-600 μM, Sigma Aldrich, St. Louis, USA) and mixed (30 Hz, 1 min), cooled(N2(l)), mixed( 30 Hz, 2 min). Then 500 µl 1x phosphate buffered saline (PBS) were added and the samples were mixed trice ( 30 sec, 20 Hz) and once (30 sec, 25 Hz). Of the obtained homogenate, 10 µl were taken for protein quantification, the samples were stored at -80 °C.

f. Inhomogenous samples were homogenized in 500 µl 1x phosphate buffered saline (PBS) with an ULTRA-TURRAX (Ika, Stauffen, Germany), washed between same tissue samples with 1x PBS, and between tissues with 1x PBS, 70 % EtOH (fresh) and 1x PBS (fresh) thoroughly. 1 spoon glass beads were added, and the samples were mixed (4x 30 sec, 20 Hz), 10 µl were taken for protein quantification, the samples stored at -80 °C.

g. Corresponding volumes for 300 µg protein of all tissues, apart from brain here 150 µg were used, were taken and topped to 200 µl with 1x PBS in 1.5 ml screw cap vials.


References:

[1] Molecular structural diversity of mitochondrial cardiolipins. Oemer G, Lackner K, Muigg K, Krumschnabel G, Watschinger K, Sailer S, Lindner H, Gnaiger E, Wortmann SB, Werner ER, Zschocke J, Keller MA. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2018 Apr 17;115(16):4158-4163. doi: 10.1073/pnas.1719407115. Epub 2018 Apr 4. PMID:29618609

protocols.name: Extraction
protocols.description:
For lipid extraction, samples were spiked with internal standards and Folch lipid extraction was performed [1].

Internal standards included 0.5 μM each of CL(14:0)4, PE(14:0)2, PC(14:0)2, PG(14:0)2, PI(14:0)2, PA(14:0)2.


a. ~100 mg glass beads and 500 µl extraction mixture (preparation see Supplementary data) were added to the 200 µl prepared solution.

b. Mixed (20 Hz, 2 min) in precooled sample holders (~ 4 °C)

c. Sonicated for 5 mins in an ice cold bath

d. Vortexed

e. Centrifuged for 10 min at 14000 rpm.

f. The lower organic phase was transferred into a glass vial.

g. Additional 500 µl extraction mixture were added to the remaining upper phase and extractionsteps b,d,e and f repeated.

h. The joined organic phases were dried under N2 flow and the extracts stored at -20 °C for subsequent analysis.


References:

[1] Folch J, Lees M, Stanley GHS. A simple method for the isolation and purification of total lipides from animal tissues. J Biol Chem. 1957;226(1):497–50.

Lipidomics analysis

protocols.name: Mass spectrometry
protocols.description:
The UPLC system was connected via the supplied Ion Max API™ interface, operated in ESI mode, to a LTQ Velos MS (Thermo Fisher Scientific Inc, Waltham, USA). The instument settings are described below.


CL only analysis was performed as published recently [1]. For analysis the lipid extracts were solubilised in 100 µl 50/50 mobile phases mixture in the extraction glass vials and transferred to the PE autosampler vials. These were loaded in the autosampler for subsequent measurement with the above described settings. With each batch before and after an external calibration curve via measurement of 1:4 dilution steps of V0 down to V7 was recorded. After adequate numbers of samples eluent blanks and quality control standards (QC) were inserted.

All lipids were identified according to their retention time, m/z and MS/MS spectra with the help of lipid standards. For CL analysis see Oemer et al. [1].
